u00fatbol de Puerto Rico}}) represents [[Puerto Rico]] in men's international [[association football|football]] it's governed by the [[Federaci\u00f3n Puertorrique\u00f1a de F\u00fatbol]] (FPF), The team's nickname is El Hurac\u00e1n Azul meaning The Blue Hurricane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elvocero.com/deportes/se-rejuvenece-el-hurac-n-azul/article_766dee88-c927-11e9-b69d-5306f224e1a5.html|title=Se rejuvenece el Hurac\u00e1n Azul|first=Yamaira Mu\u00f1iz P\u00e9rez, EL|last=VOCERO|website=El Vocero de Puerto Rico|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> The team is a member of the [[Caribbean Football Union]] and part of [[CONCACAF]], The team has never been [[FIFA World Cup]] and [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]].\n\n== History ==\n\n=== 1940\u20131990 ===\nPuerto Rico's first international match was against [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]] in 1940 in which they drew 1\u20131. They did not record a win until a 3\u20130 result in 1970 against [[Bahamas national football team|the Bahamas]]. In 1972, Puerto Rico recorded a 1\u20130 win against [[Panama national football team|Panama]] in a [[Exhibition game|friendly]]. Wins between the 1980s and 1990s were mainly against the Bahamas, the [[Dominican Republic national football team|Dominican Republic]], and [[Martinique national football team|Martinique]].<ref name=\"rsssf.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesp/prico-intres.html |title=Puerto Rico&nbsp;\u2013 List of International Matches |website=rsssf.com |publisher=Rec Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=31 January 2007 |accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Chris Armas years (1993\u20131994) ===\n[[Chris Armas]] played for Puerto Rico in the [[1993 Caribbean Cup]]. In the tournament, Puerto Rico established a 4-game win streak without conceding a goal.<ref name=\"rsssf.com\"/> The competition was not then recognized by [[FIFA]], and so his five matches were considered [[Exhibition game|friendlies]]. As a result, he was later allowed to switch his allegiance to the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States of America]],<ref>\n{{cite news |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCN/is_6_23/ai_69057380 |date = February 2001|accessdate=10 December 2007 |title=Now You See Him |work=Soccer Digest |first=Michael  |last=Lewis  |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071221001642/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCN/is_6_23/ai_69057380 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate =21 December 2007}}\n</ref> for whom he has since been capped over fifty times.\n\n=== 1995\u20132007 ===\nPuerto Rico did not record a win, and had only four draws. During this time, the team dropped down in the [[FIFA World Rankings|FIFA Rankings]] to 202nd.<ref name=\"rsssf.com\"/>\n\n=== 2008\u20132015 ===\n[[File:PUR vs Spain.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Puerto Rico (in blue) playing [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in 2012.]]\nOver the past few years, Puerto Rico has begun to emerge as a contender, like they were in the 1990s. In 2008, they drew with [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]]. They also won for the first time since 1994 when they beat the [[Dominican Republic national football team|Dominican Republic]] in the first round of the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] [[FIFA World Cup qualification|qualifiers]]. Although they lost the first leg 4\u20130 to [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]], they fought a 2\u20132 tie in the home leg in the second round. The [[Puerto Rican Football Federation]] has announced plans that would allow them to participate in the next editions of the [[Caribbean Cup]] and [[CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.primerahora.com/diario/noticia/futbol/accion_deportiva/con_la_mira_en_la_copa_de_oro_2011/318405 |title=Primerahora.com |website=primerahora.com |publisher=GFR Media LLC|date= |accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nPuerto Rico were supposed to make their debut in the [[2010 Central American and Caribbean Games|21st Central American and Caribbean Games in 2010]] on home soil in [[Mayag\u00fcez, Puerto Rico|Mayag\u00fcez]], but due to the controversy of [[CONCACAF]] not approving the stadiums, the team couldn't compete in the football event. The team was supposed to play in [[Venezuela]] instead but due to the lack of teams, the male event was canceled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meta.pr/content/futbol-femenino-arranca-manana-en-venezuela |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2 August 2010|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708053346/http://www.meta.pr/content/futbol-femenino-arranca-manana-en-venezuela |archivedate=8 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nPuerto Rico faced [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|World]] and [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final|European]] champion [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in a friendly on 15 August 2012, losing 2\u20131 in the [[Juan Ram\u00f3n Loubriel Stadium]] in [[Bayam\u00f3n, Puerto Rico]].\n\nOn 5 June 2015, Puerto Rico played a friendly against [[Bermuda national football team|Bermuda]], their last friendly before the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification&nbsp;\u2013 CONCACAF Second Round|qualifiers]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] ending in a 1\u20131 draw. After losing to [[Grenada national football team|Grenada]] 2\u20131 in the second round of the 2018 World Cup qualifiers, Puerto Rico's Interim coach Jose 'Cukito' Martinez resigned and a few days later, the [[Uruguayan]] Carlos Avedissian solved his visa problems and could finally arrive as the head coach of the national team. On 11 December 2015, Puerto Rico played a friendly against [[Major League Soccer|MLS]] team [[New York City FC|New York City]] losing 2\u20131.\n\n=== 2016\u20132017 ===\n====[[Jack Stefanowski]] era====\nOn 22 May 2016, Puerto Rico played a friendly match against the [[United States]] for the first time ever ending in a 3\u20131 loss.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://noticias.elhuracanazulpr.com/2016/05/puerto-rico-cae-en-renido-amistoso-ante.html|title=Puerto Rico cae en re\u00f1ido amistoso ante USA|first=Publicado por Javier|last=Torres|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> They advanced for the first time to the third round of the [[2017 Caribbean Cup qualification]] when they defeated [[Grenada national football team|Grenada]] and [[Antigua and Barbuda national football team|Antigua and Barbuda]] in the second round, only two games away from reaching the [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|CONCACAF Gold Cup]] for the first time. Stefanowski had to leave the technical director position because he was an assistant in Puerto Rico FC.\n\n====[[Carlos Garc\u00eda Cantarero]] era====\nThe team played three friendlies, two against Dominican Republic and one against India, prior to the third round matches against Antigua and Barbuda and Cura\u00e7ao. Puerto Rico lost the decisive match against Cura\u00e7ao after being 2\u22120 up front for which Cura\u00e7ao as head of group advanced to the Gold Cup.\n\nPuerto Rico didn't play an international match until the summer of 2017 when they played to a scoreless draw against Indonesia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://noticias.elhuracanazulpr.com/2017/06/renido-empate-ante-indonesia.html|title=Re\u00f1ido empate ante Indonesia|first=Publicado por Javier|last=Torres|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the devastation of [[Hurricane Maria]] in September that left the entire island powerless. On 7 October it was reported [[Major League Soccer|MLS]] club, [[Orlando City SC]] announced a ''Fuerza Puerto Rico\u2019 Friendly'' for 4 November with all the net proceeds from the match going towards the ''United for Puerto Rico'' initiative to raise funds and aid recovery efforts for the island. Reactivating the national team for a 3rd time this year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://futbolboricua.co/la-seleccion-se-activa-en-beneficio-de-reconstruccion-de-puerto-rico/|title=La Selecci\u00f3n se activa en beneficio de reconstrucci\u00f3n de Puerto Rico &#124; FutbolBoricua.net|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> The friendly marked Orlando City\u2019s last game of 2017, as well team captain, [[Kak\u00e1]] with the lions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://futbolboricua.co/kaka-jugara-su-ultimo-partido-contra-puerto-rico/|title=Kak\u00e1 jugar\u00e1 su \u00faltimo partido contra Puerto Rico &#124; FutbolBoricua.net|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Puerto Rico lost the exhibition match 6-1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://noticias.elhuracanazulpr.com/2017/11/cae-puerto-rico-6-1-ante-orlando-city-sc.html|title=Cae Puerto Rico 6-1 ante Orlando City SC|first=Publicado por Javier|last=Torres|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nIn May 2018, the Puerto Rican Football Federation announced that Carlos Cantarero wouldn't continue as the head coach of the national teams, with former Honduran player Amado Guevara taking over as head coach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://noticias.elhuracanazulpr.com/2018/05/fpf-anuncia-salida-de-los-tecnicos.html|title=FPF anuncia salida de los t\u00e9cnicos nacionales|first=Publicado por Javier|last=Torres|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Team image==\n\n===Colors===\n\n====Kit suppliers====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|- style=\"color:white;\"\n!  style=\"width:100px; background:#0040EF;\"|Provider\n!  style=\"width:80px; background:#0040EF;\"|Period\n|-\n| {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Joma]]\n| 2018\u2013\n|}\n\n== Tournament results ==\n\n=== Caribbean Cup ===\n* [[1989 Caribbean Cup|1989]] to [[1990 Caribbean Cup|1990]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Did not enter''\n* [[1991 Caribbean Cup|1991]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Did not qualify''\n* [[1992 Caribbean Cup|1992]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Did not enter''\n* [[1993 Caribbean Cup|1993]]&nbsp;\u2013 Final group stage\n* [[1994 Caribbean Cup|1994]] to [[1995 Caribbean Cup|1995]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Did not qualify''\n* [[1996 Caribbean Cup|1996]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Did not enter''\n* [[1997 Caribbean Cup|1997]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Withdrew''\n* [[1998 Caribbean Cup|1998]] to [[2005 Caribbean Cup|2005]]&nbsp;\u2013 ''Did not qualify''\n* [[2007 Caribbean Cup|2007]] to [[2008 Cari