o a Christian church on the orders of Emperor [[Constantine the Great|Constantine I]] (the Church of ''Agios Georgios'').{{#tag:ref|\"Originally the [[Arch of Galerius and Rotunda#Rotunda of Galerius|Rotonda]] formed part of a larger complex of buildings including a [[triumphal arch]] over the [[Via Egnatia]], a hippodrome, an octagonal building and several palaces built by [[Galerius]]. The Rotonda, as it is called in Greek (with an 'o'), is one of the largest, covered, round Roman buildings still standing today and it is a valuable historical monument on architectural grounds alone. The [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon in Rome]] is a comparable structure... ...Between the 10th and the 12th centuries,\nand again between 1525 and 1591, the Rotonda served as the main cathedral of Thessaloniki... ...In 1962 the Greek government declared the Rotonda a 'historical conservation monument (istoriko diatiriteo mnimeio) and an archaeological space'. And in 1986 UNESCO included it in its catalogue of international heritage monuments.\"<ref>Charles Stewart. ''Who Owns the Rotonda?: Church vs. State in Greece.'' '''ANTHROPOLOGY TODAY''' Vol 14 No 5, October 1998. pp. 3-4.</ref>|group=note}}\n\n*306-37 Reign of Emperor [[Constantine I|Constantine the Great]].{{#tag:ref|\"In the history of the Roman Empire and late [[Greek culture]], the reign of [[Constantine I]] forms a break. The [[Edict of Milan|agreements reached at Milan in 313 A.D.]] between Constantine and Licinius to place Christianity on an equal footing with the other religions, and besides this to build Constantinople on the Bosporus, mark the beginning of a new era. Constantine laid the foundations of the later [[Byzantine Empire]], which was based on Roman political ideas, on the [[Greek people]] and on [[Greek culture]]. Once more, thanks to Constantine, the political and cultural primacy shifted from the West to the East.\"<ref name=BENGTSON1>Hermann Bengtson. ''History of Greece: From the Beginnings to the Byzantine Era.'' Translated and Updated by Edmund F. Bloedow. University of Ottawa Press, 1988. pp. 345\u2013346.</ref>|group=note}}\n*311 [[Edict of Toleration by Galerius]] officially ending the [[Diocletian persecution]] of [[Christianity]];<ref>[[Fergus Millar]]. ''The Roman Near East: 31 BC \u2013 AD 337.'' 2nd Ed. Harvard University Press, 1993. pp. 179-180. {{ISBN|9780674778863}}</ref> Martyrdom of Bp. [[Methodius of Olympus]].<ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/3900/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u039c\u03b5\u03b8\u03cc\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f41 \u1f39\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03c1\u03c4\u03c5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u1f18\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f48\u03bb\u03cd\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5].'' 20 \u0399\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=101759 Hieromartyr Methodius the Bishop of Patara].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref>\n\n[[File:As-Constantine-XR RIC vII 019.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A coin of Constantine (c.337) showing a depiction of his [[Labarum]] standard spearing a serpent.]]\n*313 '''[[Edict of Milan]]''' issued by [[Constantine I|Constantine the Great]] and co-emperor Licinius, officially declaring [[religious freedom]] in the Roman Empire.<ref name=BENGTSON1/><ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. pp.53\u201354.</ref>{{#tag:ref|\"This law went further than [[Edict of Toleration by Galerius|Galerius' edict of toleration]] in 311, \"by the raising, in a formal juristic manner, of each individual church, and therefore the whole, the universal Church, to the level of a full juristic personality: this was the acknowledgement of the Church as a ''corpus'' in a juristic sense.\" \"<ref>T. G. Elliott. ''The Christianity of Constantine the Great.'' Scranton: University of Scranton Press, 1996. p. 119.</ref>|group=note}}\n*314 [[Synod of Ancyra|Council of Ancyra]] held.<ref>Schaff, Philip (1819\u20131893). ''[http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf214.viii.iii.i.html The Council of Ancyra. A.D. 314].'' NPNF2-14. The Seven Ecumenical Councils. Edinburgh: T&T Clark., 1900.</ref>\n*316 Death of [[Saint Blaise|Blaise of Sebaste]].<ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/2093/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u0392\u03bb\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f41 \u1f39\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03c1\u03c4\u03c5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u1f08\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03b5\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a3\u03b5\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03af\u03b1\u03c2].'' 11 \u03a6\u03b5\u03b2\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=100501 Hieromartyr Blaise the Bishop of Sebaste].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref>\n*319 Matyrdom of '''[[Theodore Stratelates]]''' (\"the General\"), under Licinius.<ref>''[http://ocafs.oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?FSID=100462 Greatmartyr Theodore Stratelates \"the General\"].'' [[Orthodox Church in America|OCA]] \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref><ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/2062/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u0398\u03b5\u03cc\u03b4\u03c9\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f41 \u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03c1\u03c4\u03c5\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u1f41 \u03a3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b7\u03bb\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2].'' \u03a6\u03b5\u03b2\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref>\n*321 Constantine the Great introduced the '''first civil legislation declaring [[Sunday]] a holiday''' in honor of the [[Resurrection of Jesus|Resurrection]].<ref name=BRITANNICA-SUNDAY>''\"Sunday.\"'' Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. '''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica 2009 Ultimate Reference Suite.'''  Chicago: Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, 2009.</ref>{{#tag:ref|He decreed that all work should cease on Sunday, except that farmers could work if necessary. This law, aimed at providing time for worship, was followed later in the same century and in subsequent centuries by further restrictions on Sunday activities.<ref name=BRITANNICA-SUNDAY/>|group=note}}\n*c. 324 The '''[[Labarum#Iconographic career under Constantine|Labarum]] with the \"[[Chi Rho|Chi-Rho]]\" [[Christogram]]''' became the official standard of the Roman Empire,<ref name=BRITTANICA-LABARUM>''\"labarum.\"'' Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. '''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica 2009 Ultimate Reference Suite.'''  Chicago: Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, 2009.</ref> after the final encounter between Roman emperors Constantine I and Licinius at the [[Battle of Chrysopolis]].{{#tag:ref|\"According to the 4th-century historian [[Eusebius]], in his ''[[Life of Constantine]]'', before the victory over Maxentius (312), Constantine saw a sign of the cross in the sky and the words \"[[En touto nika|in this sign thou shalt conquer]]\" and used it as a talisman in battle. Dating of the labarum is attested by coins issued at Constantinople (now Istanbul) after Constantine's victory over Licinius in 324.\"<ref name=BRITTANICA-LABARUM/>|group=note}}\n\n==Patriarchate of the Roman era (325\u2013732)==\n\n===Nicene era (325\u2013451)===\n[[File:THE FIRST COUNCIL OF NICEA.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The [[First Ecumenical Council]] in Nicaea, AD 325.]]\n\n*325 '''[[First Ecumenical Council]]''' held in Nicea, condemning [[Arianism]], setting the [[Computus|Paschalion]], and issuing the first version of the [[Nicene Creed]], also establishing the supremacy of honor of the Apostolic Sees as ''Rome'', followed by ''Alexandria'', ''Antioch'', and ''Jerusalem''.<ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. pp.57\u201358.</ref>\n*326 Church of [[Panagia Ekatontapiliani|Panagia Ekatontapyliani]] (Hundred Doors) in Paros founded by St. [[Helena (Empress)|Helen]], during her pilgrimage to the [[Holy Land]].<ref>Yannos Kourayos. ''Paros, Antiparos: History, Monuments, Museum.'' Adam Editions-Pergamos, 2004. p.53. {{ISBN|9789605004354}}</ref>\n[[File:Constantine I Hagia Sophia.jpg|thumb|left|150px|St. [[Constantine the Great]], [[Equal-to-the-Apostles]] (\u2020337).]]\n\n*330 '''Byzantium refounded as ''Constantinople / [[New Rome]]'' ''', Christian capital of the Roman Empire, and is dedicated to the [[Theotokos]] by Emperor [[Constantine the Great|Constantine]].<ref>T. G. Elliott (Professor). ''The Christianity of Constantine the Great.'' Scranton: University of Scranton Press, 1996. p. 255. {{ISBN|0-940866-59-5}}</ref><ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/3100/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u039c\u03bd\u03ae\u03bc\u03b7 \u1f10\u03b3\u03ba\u03b1\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03c9\u03bd \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u039a\u03c9\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03c9\u03c2].'' 11 \u039c\u03b1\u0390\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=107791 Commemoration of the Founding of Constantinople].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref>{{#tag:ref|\"The [[East Roman Empire]] was a fascinating blend of [[Hellenic Culture]], Christian faith, and Roman principles of administration and law. Precisely when this blend passed into the style called Byzantine is a much argued point. The inception certainly was the building of Constantinople early in the 4th century. Yet as late as the reign of [[Justinian I|Justinian]] the language of the court was still officially [[Latin]]; Justinian himself directed the great compilation in Latin of the ''[[Corpus Juris Civilis|Corpis iuris civilis]]'', the form in which later ages knew Roman law. Justnian, however, closed the pagan philosophical schools of Athens and abolished the consulate in 541 as a meaningless survival; from this period on, arts and letters entered ever more into the distinctive Byzantine world.\"<ref>[[Chester G. Starr]]. ''A History of the Ancient World.'' 4th ed. New York, Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1991. pp. 704-705.</ref>|group=note}}\n*333 [[Constantine the Great|Constantine]] commissions [[Eusebius of Caesarea|Eusebius]], to prepare 50 copies of the Bible for churches in the new capital.<ref>T. G. Elliott (Professor). ''The Christianity of Constantine the Great.'' Scranton: University of Scranton Press, 1996. p. 257. {{ISBN|0-940866-59-5}}</ref>\n*335 Building of the ''Protaton'' church at [[Karyes (Athos)]], dedicated to the [[Dormition]] of the Virgin Mary, oldest church on Mount Athos.\n*337 Under [[Constantine the Great]] Greece was part of the prefectures of Macedonia and Thrace; death of '''[[Constantine the Great]], [[Equal-to-the-Apostles]]'''.\n*c. 337 Death of Bishop Parthenios of [[Lampsacus]].<ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/2051/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f4d\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c1\u03b8\u03ad\u03bd\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f18\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u039b\u03b1\u03bc\u03c8\u03ac\u03ba\u03bf\u03c5].'' 7 \u03a6\u03b5\u03b2\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=100457 St Parthenius the Bishop of Lampsacus on the Hellespont].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref>\n*340\u2013570 [[Constantinople]] overtakes Rome as the [[List of largest cities throughout history|largest city in the world]] by population.<ref name=Chandler>Tertius Chandler. ''Four Thousand Years of Urban Growth: An Historical Census.'' Lewiston, NY: The Edwin Mellen Press, 1987. {{ISBN|0-88946-207-0}}.\n:(Chandler defined a city as a continuously built-up area (urban) with suburbs but without farmland inside the municipality.)</ref>\n\n*c. 342\u2013343 Death of [[Saint Nicholas|Nicholas of Myra]].<ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/1370/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u039d\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03bb\u03b1\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f41 \u0398\u03b1\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c2 \u1f08\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03b5\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u039c\u03cd\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u039b\u03c5\u03ba\u03af\u03b1\u03c2].'' 6 \u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=103484 St Nicholas the Wonderworker and Archbishop of Myra in Lycia].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref><ref>Carol Myers and Jim Rosenthal. ''[http://www.stnicholascenter.org/pages/who-is-st-nicholas/ Who is St. Nicholas?].'' St. Nicholas Center. Retrieved: 11 September 2012.</ref>\n*346 '''Apparition of the Sign of the [[Christian cross|Cross]] over Jerusalem''', in time of Patriarch Cyril, when a luminous Cross appeared over Jerusalem, stretching from Golgotha to the Mount of Olives.<ref name=SYNAX346CROSS>Great Synaxaristes: {{in lang|el}} ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/3048/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u039c\u03bd\u03ae\u03bc\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6 \u1f10\u03bd \u03c4\u1ff7 \u03bf\u1f50\u03c1\u03b1\u03bd\u1ff7 \u03c6\u03b1\u03bd\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c3\u03b7\u03bc\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6 \u03a4\u03b9\u03bc\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf\u1fe6 \u1f10\u03c0\u1f76 \u039a\u03c9\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03af\u03bf\u03c5].'' 7 \u039c\u03b1\u0390\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref>{{#tag:ref|\n* The '''First Appearance of the Cross occurred on October12, 312''': Emperor Constantine the Great had a vision of the cross in broad daylight, with the inscription ''' ''\"[[In hoc signo vinces|En Touto Nika]]\"'' ''' (''\"In this sign you will conquer\"'').\n* The '''Second Appearance of the Cross occurred on 7 May 346''': View in Jerusalem in the time of Patriarch Cyril. All the people saw the Cross of divine light spreading from Golgotha to the Mount of Olives.<ref name=SYNAX346CROSS/> \n* The '''Third Appearance of the Cross occurred on 14 September 1925''': Appearance of the Sign of the Cross over the church of St. John the Theologian at Mount Hymettus in suburban Athens, on the eve of the feast of the Exaltation of the All-Honourable and Life-giving Cross.<ref>''[http://orthodoxinfo.com/ecumenism/cross_sign.aspx The Appearance of the Sign of the Cross Near Athens in 1925].'' Orthodox Christian Information Center. Retrieved: 15 July 2015. \n:*From: ''Orthodox Life,'' Vol. 22, No. 2 (March\u2013April, 1972), pp. 18-20.</ref>|group=note}}\n\n[[File:SPYRIDON.jpg|thumb|right|150px|St. [[Saint Spyridon|Spyridon]], Bishop of Trimythous.]]\n*348 Death of '''[[Saint Spyridon|Spyridon of Trimythous]]'''.<ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/1430/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c0\u03c5\u03c1\u03af\u03b4\u03c9\u03bd \u1f41 \u0398\u03b1\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c2 \u1f18\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a4\u03c1\u03b9\u03bc\u03c5\u03b8\u03bf\u1fe6\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03cd\u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5].'' 12 \u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=103526 St Spyridon the Wonderworker and Bishop of Tremithus].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref>\n*c. 354 Emperor Constantius II sent the [[Arianism|Arian]] bishop [[Theophilos the Indian]] on mission to south Asia via Arabia where he is said to have converted the [[Himyarite Kingdom|Himyarites]] and built three churches in southwest Arabia; he is also said to have found Christians in India.<ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p.65.</ref>\n*357 The [[Praetorian prefecture of Illyricum]] is formed when the three dioceses of [[Diocese of Macedonia|Macedonia]], [[Diocese of Dacia|Dacia]] and [[Diocese of Pannonia|Pannonia]] were first grouped together by [[Constantius II]].\n*358 [[Basil of Caesarea|Basil the Great]] founds monastery of Annesos in Pontus, the model for Eastern [[monasticism]].<ref>[[Adrian Fortescue|Fortescue, Adrian]]. ''\"[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/10467a.htm Eastern Monasticism].\"'' '''The Catholic Encyclopedia.''' Vol. 10. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911.</ref>\n*359 Councils of [[Council of Seleucia|Seleucia]] in the east and [[Council of Rimini|Rimini]] in the west.<ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. pp.66\u201367.</ref>\n*360 First church of [[Hagia Sophia]] inaugurated by Emperor [[Constantius II]].<ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p.67.</ref>\n*364 [[Council of Laodicea]] held.\n[[File:3 Holy Hierarchs.jpg|left|thumb|240px|The '''[[Three Holy Hierarchs]]''', Basil the Great (''Basil of Caesarea''), Gregory the Theologian (''Gregory of Nazianzus'') and John Chrysostom. ]]\n\n*c.368 '''[[Basil of Caesarea|Basil the Great]] codifies the ethical precepts of monastic life''' in his ''Asketika'' (sometimes mistranslated as ''Rules'' of St. Basil), thus remembered as a father of [[Cenobitic monasticism|communal monasticism]] in Eastern Christianity.<ref name=DBH57>David Bentley Hart. ''The Story of Christianity: An Illustrated History of 2000 Years of the Christian Faith.'' London: Quercus Editions Ltd. 2011 edition. p. 57.</ref>{{#tag:ref|[[Basil of Caesarea|Basil]] established guidelines for monastic life which focus on community life, liturgical prayer, and manual labour. Together with [[Pachomius the Great|Pachomius]] he is remembered as a father of [[Cenobitic monasticism|communal monasticism]] in Eastern Christianity.|group=note}}\n*375 [[Basil of Caesarea|Basil the Great]] writes ''On the Holy Spirit'', confirming the divinity of the [[Holy Spirit]].\n*377 [[Epiphanius of Salamis]] (Cyprus) writes ''[[Panarion]] (\u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03ac\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd, \"Medicine Chest\"), also known as Adversus Haereses (\"Against Heresies\")'', listing 80 heresies, some of which are not described in any other surviving documents from the time .\n*378 Visigoths defeat Emperor Valens at the [[Battle of Adrianople]], permanently weakening northern borders of the empire.\n*379 Death of Basil the Great; the '''[[Cappadocian Fathers]]''' [[Basil of Caesarea|Basil the Great]], [[Gregory of Nazianzus|Gregory of Nazianzus the Theologian]], and [[Gregory of Nyssa]] set their mark on all subsequent history of the Greek churches, through Basil's ''On the Holy Spirit'', and ''Rules''; Gregory of Nazianzus' ''Five Theological Orations''; and Gregory of Nyssa's polemical works against various heretical teachings.<ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p.71.</ref>\n*380 Christianity established as the official faith of the Roman Empire by Emperor [[Theodosius I|Theodosius the Great]].\n[[File:Theodosius I's empire.png|right|thumb|250px|The division of the Empire after the death of [[Theodosius I]], c. 395 AD superimposed on modern borders. {{legend|#B53637|Western Roman Empire}} {{legend|#8F36B5|Eastern Roman Empire}}]]\n\n*381 '''[[Second Ecumenical Council]]''' held in Constantinople, condemning [[Macedonians (religious group)|Macedonianism/Pneumatomachianism]] and [[Apollinarism|Appollinarianism]], declaring the divinity of the Holy Spirit, confirming the previous [[Ecumenical Council]], and completing the [[Nicene Creed#The Niceno\u2013Constantinopolitan Creed|Nicene-Constantinopolitan Creed]].\n*383 First monastic institution established in Constantinople at [[Samatya|Psamathia]], outside the city.<ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p.73.</ref>\n*386 '''[[S\u00fcmela Monastery|Panagia Soumela Monastery]]''' founded in Trebizond, Pontus, Asia Minor, after [[Luke the Evangelist|St. Luke's]] Icon of the [[Theotokos|Mother of God]] appears at Mt. Mela.\n*389 Death of [[Gregory of Nazianzus|Gregory the Theologian]].<ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/1881/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u0393\u03c1\u03b7\u03b3\u03cc\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f41 \u0398\u03b5\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f08\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03b5\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03c9\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03c9\u03c2].'' 25 \u0399\u03b1\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=100298 St Gregory the Theologian the Archbishop of Constantinople].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref>\n*391-92 Closing of all non-Christian temples in the Empire;<ref name=STARR>[[Chester G. Starr]]. ''A History of the Ancient World.'' 4th ed. New York, Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1991. p. 680.</ref> [[Theodosius I|Theodosius the Great]] ends pagan [[Eleusinian Mysteries]] by decree.{{#tag:ref|\"Their secrecy notwithstanding, the [[Eleusinian Mysteries|mysteries of Eleusis]] are more extensively documented than any other single Greek cult...From the earliest testimony, the Eleusinian section of the [[Homeric Hymns|Homeric ''Hymn to Demeter'']], to the proscription of the cult by [[Theodosius I|Theodosius]] and the destruction of the sanctuary by the Goths about 400 AD [396 AD], we survey a period of a thousand years. During this time the cult drew men and women from all of Greece and later from the whole of the Roman Empire.\"<ref>[[Walter Burkert]]. ''Greek Religion, Archaic and Classical.'' Transl. John Raffan. [[Basil Blackwell]], 1985. p. 285.</ref>|group=note}}\n*c. 394 Death of '''[[Gregory of Nyssa]]''';<ref>''\"Gregory of Nyssa, Saint.\"'' Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. '''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica 2009 Ultimate Reference Suite'''. Chicago: Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, 2009.</ref><ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/1686/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u0393\u03c1\u03b7\u03b3\u03cc\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f18\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u039d\u03cd\u03c3\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2].'' 10 \u0399\u03b1\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref>\n*394 [[Epiphanius of Salamis]] (Cyprus) attacks teachings of [[Origen]] as heretical.\n[[File:Johnchrysostom.jpg|left|thumb|240px|St. [[John Chrysostom]], Abp. of Constantinople (398\u2013404).]]\n\n*395 Re-division of Empire with death of Emperor Theodosius the Great, by which time Christianity was definitely the [[state religion]];<ref name=STARR/> Theodosius I divided the prefecture of Macedonia into the provinces of Creta, Achaea, Thessalia, Epirus Vetus, Epirus Nova, and Macedonia; the Aegean islands formed the province of Insulae in the prefecture of Asiana; the placing of the cincture (sash) of the Most Holy [[Theotokos]] in the Church of the Virgin in Halkoprateia-Constantinople (395\u2013408).<ref>Great Synaxaristes: {{in lang|el}} ''[http://synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/501/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u039a\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac\u03b8\u03b5\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 \u03a4\u03b9\u03bc\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u0396\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u0398\u03b5\u03bf\u03c4\u03cc\u03ba\u03bf\u03c5].'' 31 \u0391\u03c5\u03b3\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/saints/lives/2013/08/31/102442-the-placing-of-the-cincture-sash-of-the-most-holy-mother-of-god The Placing of the Cincture (Sash) of the Most Holy Mother of God].'' OCA - Lives of the Saints.</ref>\n*398 '''[[John Chrysostom]]''' becomes Abp. of Constantinople.\n*399 Death of '''[[Evagrius Ponticus]]''', the first monk to write extensively on the spiritual life, recording and systematizing the oral teachings of the desert fathers, and influencing his students [[Palladius of Galatia|Palladius]] and [[John Cassian]], [[Maximus the Confessor]], [[Diadochos of Photiki]], [[Isaac of Nineveh]], [[Symeon the New Theologian]], and [[Gregory Palamas]], among others.<ref name=DBH57/><ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p.77.</ref>\n[[File:Roman Empire with dioceses in 400 AD.png|right|thumb|250px|Map of the Roman Empire with its Dioceses, in 400 AD. The Prefecture of \"Eastern Illyricum\" (''Illyricum Orientale'') consisted of the Dioceses of [[Diocese of Dacia|Dacia]] and [[Diocese of Macedonia|Macedonia]].]]\n\n*403 [[Synod of the Oak]] held near Chalcedon, deposing and exiling [[John Chrysostom]], whose principal opponent was [[Severian of Gabala]], who served as prosecutor and judge of the patriarch.<ref name=BRIT-GABALA>''\"Severian Of Gabala.\"'' Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. '''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica 2009 Ultimate Reference Suite'''. Chicago: Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, 2009.</ref>\n*407 Death of John Chrysostom in exile;<ref name=BRIT-GABALA/> erection of the ''' ''Eudoxiana'' ''' in Gaza, a large beautiful church with thirty-two large marble columns,{{#tag:ref|The church was constructed directly upon the ruins of The Marneion, the temple sacred to [[Zeus|Zeus Marnas]], who was the local Hellenistic incarnation of [[Dagon]]. It was the last surviving great cult center of paganism, and was burned by order of the Roman emperor in 402 AD. After the Muslim conquest in the 7th century, the Church of St. Porphyrios (''Eudoxiana'') in Gaza City, founded as a Byzantine Church in 407 AD, was transformed into the [[Great Mosque of Gaza]].|group=note}} erected at the expense of Empress [[Aelia Eudoxia|Eudoxia]] during the tenure of Bp. [[Porphyrios of Gaza]], and [[Consecrations in Eastern Christianity#Consecration of a church|dedicated]] on [[Easter|Pascha]] (14 April), 407 AD.<ref name=PORPHYRIOSGAZA>Great Synaxaristes: {{in lang|el}} ''[http://synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/2244/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a0\u03bf\u03c1\u03c6\u03cd\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f18\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u0393\u03ac\u03b6\u03b7\u03c2].'' 26 \u03a6\u03b5\u03b2\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref>{{#tag:ref|{{in lang|el}} \"\u039a\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac\u03c6\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5 \u03b4\u1f72 \u1f41 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u1f70 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u03b4\u03b1\u03c6\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u1fd6 \u03c4\u1f78 \u039c\u03b1\u03c1\u03bd\u03b5\u1fd6\u03bf\u03bd, \u1f41 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af\u03c6\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bd\u03b1\u1f78\u03c2 \u03c4\u1ff6\u03bd \u1f18\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u1ff6\u03bd \u0393\u03b1\u03b6\u03b1\u03af\u03c9\u03bd, \u03c0\u03bf\u1f7a \u03b5\u1f36\u03c7\u03b5 \u1f31\u03b4\u03c1\u03c5\u03b8\u03b5\u1fd6 \u1f00\u03c0\u1f78 \u03c4\u1f78\u03bd \u03b1\u1f50\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03ac\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b1 \u1f08\u03b4\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1\u03bd\u1f78 \u03c4\u1f78 \u1f14\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 129 \u03bc.\u03a7. \u03a3\u03c4\u1f74\u03bd \u03b8\u03ad\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u1f00\u03bd\u03bf\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf\u03bc\u03ae\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b5 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u1f74\u03c2 \u03bd\u03b1\u1f78\u03c2 \u03bc\u1f72 \u03c7\u03bf\u03c1\u03b7\u03b3\u03af\u03b1 \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u03b1\u1f50\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03ac\u03c4\u03b5\u03b9\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u0395\u1f50\u03b4\u03bf\u03be\u03af\u03b1\u03c2, \u1f21 \u1f41\u03c0\u03bf\u03af\u03b1 \u1f00\u03c0\u03ad\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03b9\u03bb\u03b5 \u03b3\u03b9\u1f70 \u03c4\u1f78\u03bd \u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u1f78 \u03b1\u1f50\u03c4\u1f78 \u03c3\u03c4\u1f74\u03bd \u0393\u03ac\u03b6\u03b1 \u03c4\u1f78\u03bd \u1f08\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c7\u03ad\u03b1 \u1f00\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03c4\u03ad\u03ba\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd\u03b1 \u03a1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c6\u03af\u03bd\u03bf. \u1f49 \u03bd\u03b1\u1f78\u03c2 \u03b1\u1f50\u03c4\u03cc\u03c2, \u03c0\u03bf\u1f7a \u1f40\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03ba\u03b5 \u0395\u1f50\u03b4\u03bf\u03be\u03b9\u03b1\u03bd\u03cc\u03c2, \u03b5\u1f36\u03c7\u03b5 32 \u03bc\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03ba\u03af\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u1f00\u03c0\u1f78 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u1f78 \u03bc\u03ac\u03c1\u03bc\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03c4\u1f70 \u1f10\u03b3\u03ba\u03b1\u03af\u03bd\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u1f14\u03b3\u03b9\u03bd\u03b1\u03bd \u03c4\u1f78 \u03a0\u03ac\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6 407 \u03bc.\u03a7.\"|group=note}}\n*411 Death of [[Alexius of Rome|Alexios the Man of God]], [[Foolishness for Christ|Fool-for-Christ]].<ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/2956/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f4d\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f08\u03bb\u03ad\u03be\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f41 \u1f04\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6 \u0398\u03b5\u03bf\u1fe6].'' 17 \u039c\u03b1\u03c1\u03c4\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=100822 Venerable Alexis the Man of God].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref>\n*420 Death of Bp. '''[[Porphyrios of Gaza]]''', known for [[Missionary|Christianizing]] the recalcitrant [[pagan]] city of Gaza and having its temples demolished.<ref name=PORPHYRIOSGAZA/>\n*421 Emperor of the east [[Theodosius II]] declares war on Persia when Persia begins persecuting Christians; the persecution lasts until 457.<ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p.82.</ref>\n*425 [[University of Constantinople]] founded as the first university in the world.\n*426 '''[[Euthymius the Great]]''' establishes [[lavra]] in Palestinian desert, consecrated in 428 by Bp. [[Juvenal of Jerusalem]];<ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p.83.</ref> Synod held in Constantinople against the [[Messalians]].<ref name=MCCLINTOCKandSTRONG491>Rev. [[John McClintock (theologian)|John McClintock]] (D.D.),and [[James Strong (theologian)|James Strong]] (S.T.D.). ''[[Cyclopaedia of Biblical, Theological and Ecclesiastical Literature]].'' Vol. II - C, D. New York: Harper & Brothers Publishers, 1868. p. 491.</ref>\n*431 '''[[Third Ecumenical Council]]''' held in Ephesus, condemning [[Nestorianism]] and [[Pelagianism]], confirming the use of the term ''[[Theotokos]]'' to refer to the Virgin Mary, and confirming [[autocephaly]] of [[Cypriot Orthodox Church|Church of Cyprus]].\n*437 [[Seven Sleepers|Seven Sleepers of Ephesus]] awakened to prove resurrection of the dead.<ref name=SEVENSLEEPERS>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/290/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u039f\u1f31 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03b9 \u1f19\u03c0\u03c4\u1f70 \u03a0\u03b1\u1fd6\u03b4\u03b5\u03c2 \u1f10\u03bd \u1f18\u03c6\u03ad\u03c3\u1ff3].'' 4 \u0391\u03c5\u03b3\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=102195 7 Holy Youths \"Seven Sleepers\" of Ephesus].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref>{{#tag:ref|{{in lang|el}}: \"\u039c\u03b5\u03c4\u1f70 194 \u03c7\u03c1\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1, \u1f10\u03c0\u1f76 [[Theodosius II|\u0398\u03b5\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf\u03c3\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6 \u039c\u03b9\u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u1fe6]], \u03c3\u03c4\u1f74\u03bd \u1f1c\u03c6\u03b5\u03c3\u03bf \u03ba\u03ac\u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b1\u1f35\u03c1\u03b5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ae\u03c1\u03c5\u03c4\u03c4\u03b5 \u1f45\u03c4\u03b9 \u03b4\u1f72\u03bd \u1f51\u03c0\u03ac\u03c1\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9 \u1f00\u03bd\u03ac\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03bd\u03b5\u03ba\u03c1\u1ff6\u03bd. \u1f18\u03ba\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03b7, \u03bb\u03bf\u03b9\u03c0\u03cc\u03bd, \u03c4\u1f74\u03bd \u1f10\u03c0\u03bf\u03c7\u03ae, \u03ba\u03ac\u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03bf \u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u1f76 \u03c3\u03c4\u1f74\u03bd \u1f00\u03b3\u03bf\u03c1\u1f70 \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u1f18\u03c6\u03ad\u03c3\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c8\u03ce\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c8\u03c9\u03bc\u1f76 \u03bc\u1f72 \u03c4\u1f78 \u03bd\u03cc\u03bc\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u1f10\u03c0\u03bf\u03c7\u1fc6\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6 \u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u0391\u1f50\u03c4\u1f78 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03ba\u03ac\u03bb\u03b5\u03c3\u03b5 \u1f14\u03ba\u03c0\u03bb\u03b7\u03be\u03b7. \u03a0\u1fc6\u03c1\u03b1\u03bd, \u03bb\u03bf\u03b9\u03c0\u1f78\u03bd \u03c4\u1f78 \u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u1f76 \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03c4\u1f78 \u1f00\u03bd\u03ad\u03ba\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03b1\u03bd. \u039a\u03b1\u03c4\u03cc\u03c0\u03b9\u03bd, \u03c0\u1fc6\u03b3\u03b1\u03bd \u03c3\u03c4\u1f74 \u03c3\u03c0\u03b7\u03bb\u03b9\u1f70 \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03b2\u03c1\u1fc6\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd \u03b6\u03c9\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u1f70 \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03c4\u1f70 \u1f51\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03bf\u03b9\u03c0\u03b1 \u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b9\u03ac.\"<ref name=SEVENSLEEPERS/>|group=note}}\n*438 '''[[Codex Theodosianus]]''' published; relics of [[John Chrysostom]] brought to Constantinople and buried in the [[Church of the Holy Apostles]].\n*447 Earthquake in Constantinople, when a boy was lifted up to heaven and heard the '''[[Trisagion]]''';<ref>Great Synaxaristes: {{in lang|el}} ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/732/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u039c\u03bd\u03ae\u03bc\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6 \u03bc\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u1fe6].'' 25 \u03a3\u03b5\u03c0\u03c4\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref> Pope [[Leo the Great|Leo I]] wrote to the bishops of Sicily, rebuking them for permitting [[baptism]] at [[Epiphany (holiday)|Epiphany]], as the Greeks did, and ordering them to observe the Roman custom of baptizing on [[Easter]] and [[Pentecost|Whitsunday]].<ref name=SICILY>White, Lynn, Jr.. ''\"The Byzantinization of Sicily.\"'' '''The American Historical Review.''' Vol. 42, No. 1 (Oct., 1936). p.5.</ref>\n*449 [[Robber Synod of Ephesus]], presided over by [[Dioscorus of Alexandria]], with an order from the emperor to acquit [[Eutyches]] the [[Monophysitism|Monophysite]].\n*c. 450 Revelation of the '''[[Life-giving Spring|Life-Giving Font]]''' of the [[Mother of God]], in [[Bal\u0131kl\u0131, Istanbul|Valoukli]], Constantinople, to a soldier named Leo Marcellus (who would later become Byzantine Emperor [[Leo I the Thracian|Leo I]] (457\u2013474), becoming one of the most important [[pilgrimage]] sites in [[Greek Orthodoxy]].<ref>{{in lang|fr}} [[Raymond Janin|Janin, Raymond]] (1953). ''La G\u00e9ographie eccl\u00e9siastique de l'Empire byzantin. 1. Part: Le Si\u00e8ge de Constantinople et le Patriarcat Oecum\u00e9nique. 3rd Vol. : Les \u00c9glises et les Monast\u00e8res.'' Paris: Institut Fran\u00e7ais d'Etudes Byzantines. p.232.</ref><ref>''[http://days.pravoslavie.ru/en/Days/20120404.htm April 4/17] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231021258/http://days.pravoslavie.ru/en/Days/20120404.htm |date=31 December 2014 }}.'' Orthodox Calendar (Pravoslavie.ru).</ref>\n\n===Early Byzantine era (451\u2013843)===\n[[File:Theodore Studite (Menologion of Basil II).jpg|left|thumb|255px|Byzantine [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniature]] depicting the [[Monastery of Stoudios|Stoudios Monastery]] and the [[Propontis]] (Sea of Marmara).]]\n\n*451 '''[[Fourth Ecumenical Council]]''' meets at Chalcedon, condemning [[Eutychianism]] and [[Monophysitism]], affirming doctrine of two perfect and indivisible but distinct natures in Christ, and recognizing [[Greek Orthodox Church of Jerusalem|Church of Jerusalem]] as patriarchate.<ref>[[Henry Chadwick (theologian)|Henry Chadwick]]. ''The Early Church.'' Revised Edition. Penguin Books, 1993. pp. 203-204. {{ISBN|0-14-023199-4}}.</ref>\n*452 '''[[Beheading of John the Baptist#Related feasts|Second finding]] of the Head of [[John the Forerunner]]''', at [[Homs|Emesa]].<ref>''[http://oca.org/saints/lives/2013/02/24/100603-first-and-second-finding-of-the-honorable-head-of-the-holy-glori First and second finding of the Honorable Head of the Holy Glorious Prophet, Forerunner, and Baptist of the Lord, John].'' OCA - Lives of the Saints.</ref><ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/2234/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u0395\u1f55\u03c1\u03b5\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 \u03a4\u03b9\u03bc\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b5\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u1fc6\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6 \u1f09\u03b3\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03ae\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5, \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03c1\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03b2\u03b1\u03c0\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6 \u1f38\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7].'' 24 \u03a6\u03b5\u03b2\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref>\n*457 First coronation of Byzantine Emperor by patriarch of Constantinople;<ref name=TSAI90-91>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. pp. 90\u201391.</ref> [[Proterius of Alexandria]] is lynched by an Alexandrian mob; rejecting the Christological definitions of [[Fourth Ecumenical Council|Chalcedon]], the '''Egyptian or [[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic church]] goes its own way, becoming one of the [[Oriental Orthodoxy|Oriental Orthodox Churches]]'''.{{#tag:ref|\"Mobs in Alexandria lynch [[Proterius of Alexandria|Proterius]], a Byzantine Chalcedonian, who had been imposed upon them. They elect [[Timothy Aelurus]]. Rejecting the christological definitions of Chalcedon, the [[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Egyptian, or Coptic, church]], goes its own way, becoming one of the [[Oriental Orthodoxy|Oriental Orthodox]] churches. Small groups of Christians in Egypt and Syria, known as [[Melkites]], do accept the [[Definition of Chalcedon]]. The division is generally linguistic. From this time also, the Syrian church begins the hardening of lines between the Monophysitism of [[West Syrian Rite|West Syrians]] and the sympathizers of [[Nestorius]] among [[East Syrian Rite|East Syrians]].\"<ref name=TSAI90-91/>|group=note}}\n*458 Death of Bp. [[Theodoret|Theodoret of Cyrrhus]], influential author and theologian who played a pivotal role in many early Byzantine church controversies.\n*462 [[Indiction]] moved to 1 September; '''[[Monastery of Stoudios|Studion Monastery]] founded'''.\n[[File:Roman-Empire 477ad.jpg|right|thumb|255px|Eastern Roman Empire c. 477, showing the extent of [[Koine Greek]].]]\n\n*463 Death of [[Saint Patapios|Patapius of Thebes]].<ref>''[http://www.johnsanidopoulos.com/2009_11_09_archive.html Saint Patapios of Thebes and His Monastery in Loutraki].'' Mystagogy - Weblog (Holy Synod in Resistance - source document). 9 December 2009.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/saints/lives/2013/12/08/103494-venerable-patapius-of-thebes Venerable Patapius of Thebes].'' OCA - Lives of the Saints.</ref>{{#tag:ref|\"PATAPIUS, solitary of Constantinople, native of Thebes, the subject of three homilies written upon him by [[Andrew of Crete|ANDREAS CRETENSIS]]. He lived before the 8th century: his feast is 8 Dec..\"<ref>Rev. James Gammack, (M.A., LL.D., Aberdeen). ''\"PATAPIUS.\"'' In: [[William Smith (lexicographer)|William Smith]] and [[Henry Wace (priest)|Henry Wace]]. '''A Dictionary of Christian Biography, Literature, Sects and Doctrines'''. Volume IV: Naamanes\u2014Zuntfredus. London: John Murray, 1887. p. 198.</ref>|group=note}}\n*c. 471 Patr. [[Patriarch Acacius of Constantinople|Acacius of Constantinople]] was first called ''\"Oikoumenikos\"'' (Ecumenical).\n*476 '''Fall of the [[Western Roman Empire]]''' as [[Romulus Augustulus]], the last Western Roman emperor, is deposed by the German [[Odoacer]],<ref>James William Ermatinger. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=EdBEHD4XQ-0C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false The Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire].'' Greenwood Publishing Group, 2004. p. xxii.</ref> leaving the emperor in the Greek East as the sole imperial authority, and an unstable political environment in the West where the Church of Rome slowly developed a centralized structure, concentrating religious as well as secular authority in the office of the Pope, the [[Bishop of Rome]].{{#tag:ref|After the fall of the Western Empire, the terms \"[[Greek East and Latin West|Greek East]]\" and \"[[Greek East and Latin West|Latin West]]\" are applied to areas that were formerly part of the Eastern or Western Empires, and also to areas that fell under the Greek or Latin cultural sphere but which had never been part of the Roman Empire. In this sense, particular attention is given to differences in Christianity in the two parts, specifically between [[Western Christianity]] and [[Eastern Christianity]].|group=note}}\n*484 '''[[Acacian Schism]]'''.\n*493 Death of [[Daniel the Stylite]] an ascetic who lived for 33 years on a pillar near the city of Constantinople.\n*c. 500 [[Zosimus]], pagan Greek historian writes ''Historia Nova (\"New History\")'', a history of the Roman Empire to 410 AD, with an anti-Christian view offering a different interpretation to church affairs than from Christian sources;<ref name=TSAI99>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p.99.</ref> [[Pseudo-Dionysius the Areopagite]]'s writing corpus including the ''Divine Names'', ''Mystical Theology'', ''Celestial Hierarchy'', and ''Ecclesiastical Hierarchy'' influences the development of Byzantine mystical spirituality and hesychasm through [[Maximus the Confessor]], [[Symeon the New Theologian]], and [[Gregory Palamas]].<ref name=TSAI99/>\n*502 Start of [[Byzantine-Sassanid Wars]], lasting until 562.\n*518 Patriarch [[John of Cappadocia|John II of Constantinople]] is addressed as ''\"Oikoumenikos Patriarches\"'' (Ecumenical Patriarch); the Byzantine government begins persecution of non-Chalcedonians in the east, especially in Mesopotamia.\n\n[[File:Romanos the Melodist (Menologion of Basil II).jpg|left|thumb|200px|St. [[Romanus the Singer|Romanos]]' vision of the Virgin Mary.]]\n*519 Eastern and Western churches reconciled with end of [[Acacian Schism]].\n[[File:Ayasofya-Innenansicht.jpg|right|thumb|220px|An interior view of [[Hagia Sophia]] today.]]\n\n*520 '''[[Romanus the Singer|Romanus the Melodist]]''' the greatest hymnographer, develops the [[Kontakion]], a chanted verse sermon, to perfection; influenced by [[Ephrem the Syrian]], he in turn influences [[Andrew of Crete]].<ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p.103.</ref>\n*529 Emperor [[Justinian I|Justinian]] closes the [[The School of Athens|School of Athens]], which [[Plato]] had founded in 387 BC.<ref>Rev. A. H. Hore. ''[https://archive.org/details/cu31924029361890 Eighteen centuries of the Orthodox Greek Church].'' London: James Parker & Co. 1899. p.284.</ref>{{#tag:ref|\"In Greece the Justinian era forms the decisive break. In 529 A.D. Justinian prohibited instruction under heathen teachers, deprived the professors of the old religion of their income, and confiscated the endowed wealth belonging to the University of Athens. With this gesture he drew the line under the history of education for an entire millennium.\"<ref>Hermann Bengtson. ''History of Greece: From the Beginnings to the Byzantine Era.'' Translated and Updated by Edmund F. Bloedow. University of Ottawa Press, 1988. pp. 349.</ref>|group=note}}\n*529\u2013534 Justinian's ''' ''[[Corpus Juris Civilis]]'' ''' issued, first comprehensive legal code in history of Roman Empire; Justinian's ''Novella 131'' formulated the proposed government of universal Christendom by five patriarchal sees under the auspices of a single universal empire ([[Pentarchy (Christianity)|Pentarchy]]).\n*532 Justinian the Great orders building of '''[[Hagia Sophia]]'''.\n*533 Malta becomes part of the Byzantine Empire, being incorporated into the Byzantine province of Sicily for 337 years (533-870).<ref>Marshall Cavendish Corporation. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=xcYVmUyHG2AC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false World and Its Peoples].'' Volume 6 of Italy, Malta, and San Marino. Marshall Cavendish, 2010. p. 843.</ref>\n*537 Construction of Hagia Sophia in Constantinople completed; Justinian decrees that all dates must include the [[Indiction]].\n*537\u2013752 '''[[Byzantine Papacy]]'''.<ref>[[Andrew J. Ekonomou]]. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=zomZk6DbFTIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false Byzantine Rome and the Greek Popes: Eastern Influences on Rome and the Papacy from Gregory the Great to Zacharias, A.D. 590\u2013752].'' Roman Studies: Interdisciplinary Approaches Series. Lexington Books, 2007. 347 pp. {{ISBN|9780739119778}}</ref><ref>[[Eamon Duffy]]. ''[https://archive.org/details/00book1593273669 Saints & Sinners: A History of the Popes].'' Yale University Press, 1997. pp.72\u201385.</ref>{{#tag:ref|\"From 678 to 752, or until after Ravenna had fallen before the Lombards, out of thirteen popes, eleven were orientals... ...in the later seventh and early eighth centuries the Orientals actually formed a majority of the Roman clergy and presumably of the more influential laity as well - a thesis which seems amply substantiated by the remains of the Rome of that period.\"<ref name=SICILY13>White, Lynn, Jr.. ''\"The Byzantinization of Sicily.\"'' '''The American Historical Review.''' Vol. 42, No. 1 (Oct., 1936). p.13.</ref>|group=note}}\n*538 Emperor Justinian the Great, via deportations and force, manages to get [[Pentarchy (Christianity)|all five patriarchates]] officially into communion.<ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p. 107.</ref>\n*c. 540 Death of Osios '''[[David the Dendrite|David of Thessaloniki]]'''.<ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}} ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/3982/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f4d\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u0394\u03b1\u03b2\u1f76\u03b4 \u1f10\u03bd \u0398\u03b5\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03ba\u03b7].'' 26 \u0399\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=101817 Monkmartyr David of Thessalonica].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref>\n*540 Bulgar raids into Illyricum and northern Greece.\n*543 Doctrine of [[apokatastasis]] condemned by Synod of Constantinople; Justinian the Great sends missionaries to Nubia (the three kingdoms of [[Nobatia|Nobatia/Novatia]], [[Alodia|Alodia/Alwa]], and [[Kingdom of Makuria|Makuria]]).\n*544 According to tradition the [[Image of Edessa|Mandylion]] of Edessa destroys Persian siege works.\n[[File:Justinian Byzanz.png|left|thumb|265px|The Byzantine Empire during its greatest territorial extent under Justinian. c. 550.]]\n\n*552 Death of '''[[orthodoxwiki:Gregentios of Himyaritia|Gregentios of Himyaritia]]''',<ref name=SYNAX-GREGENTIOS>Great [[Synaxarion|Synaxaristes]] {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/1489/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f4d\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u0393\u03c1\u03b7\u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f18\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u0391\u1f30\u03b8\u03b9\u03bf\u03c0\u03af\u03b1\u03c2].'' 19 \u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref name=MOSPAT>''[http://www.holytrinityorthodox.com/calendar/los/December/19-05.htm Sainted Gregory, Bishop of Omiritia (Himyaritia)].'' HOLY TRINITY RUSSIAN ORTHODOX CHURCH (A parish of the Patriarchate of Moscow).</ref>{{#tag:ref|Also known as: Gregentios of [[Zafar, Yemen|Taphar]];<ref>Albrecht Berger (Ed.). ''[https://www.amazon.com/Gregentios-Archbishop-Taphar-Millennium-Studies/dp/3110184451 Life And Works of Saint Gregentios, Archbishop of Taphar].'' Millennium Studies 7. Walter de Gruyter, Tra edition, 30 October 2006. 915 pp. {{ISBN|9783110184457}}</ref> Gregentios of Ethiopia;<ref name=SYNAX-GREGENTIOS/> Gregentius of Himyar;<ref>''[http://www.mpc.org.mk/english/Calendar/prologue.asp?id=2177 Saint Gregentius, Bishop of Himyar].'' Macedonian Orthodox Church \u2013 Archdiocese of Ohrid.</ref> Gregentius [[Zafar, Yemen|Tephrensis]];<ref>Gregentius Tephrensis. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=SBNuYgEACAAJ&dq=inauthor:%22Gregentius+Tephrensis%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3b6SUITTKYfC0AGMjYCYBA&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAQ Disputatio cum Herbano Judaeo, Graece edita, cum Interpretatione ... N.K. Nic. Gulonij ...].'' 1603.</ref> Grigentius of Omir;<ref name=PROLOGUE>Bishop [[Nikolai Velimirovic]]. ''[http://www.westsrbdio.org/prolog/prolog.htm Saint Gregory (Grigentius), Bishop of Omir].'' The Prologue from Ohrid. Serbian Orthodox Church Diocese of Western America. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622140823/http://www.westsrbdio.org/prolog/prolog.htm |date=22 June 2013 }}</ref> Gregory of Omiritia;<ref name=MOSPAT/> or Gregory of Omirits.<ref name=OCA>''[http://oca.org/saints/lives/2013/12/19/103592-st-gregory-the-archbishop-of-omirits St Gregory the Archbishop of Omirits].'' OCA \u2013 Lives of the Saints.</ref>|group=note}} missionary Bishop of [[w:Himyarite Kingdom|Himyaritia]] (''Homer, Omirits,'' in [[w:Arabia Felix|Southern Arabia]]) for over thirty years, when the area was under [[w:Kingdom of Aksum|Aksumite]] control, playing an important role in the restoration of [[Orthodox Christianity]] there after the persecution of [[Dhu Nuwas|Dunaan]] (''Dh\u00fb Nuw\u00e2s'').<ref>Sergew Hable-Selassie. ''[http://www.dacb.org/stories/ethiopia/gregentius_.html Gregentius, fl. 6th century, Orthodox].'' Dictionary of African Christian Biography.</ref>\n*553 '''[[Fifth Ecumenical Council]]''' held in Constantinople in an attempt to reconcile Chalcedonians with non-Chalcedonians\u2013the ''[[Three-Chapter Controversy|Three Chapters]]'' of [[Theodore of Mopsuestia]], [[Theodoret|Theodoret of Cyrrhus]], and [[Ibas (Assyrian bishop)|Ibas of Edessa]] are condemned for their [[Nestorianism]], and [[Origen]] and his writings are also condemned; Ostrogoth kingdom in Italy conquered by the Byzantine Empire after the [[Battle of Mons Lactarius]]; the first evidence for a bishop on Malta dates from 553.<ref name=HMML>''[http://www.hmml.org/centers/malta/history/history.html#Muslims Brief History of Malta].'' ''' Hill Museum & Manuscript Library''' (HMML). Retrieved: 28 August 2013. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130810104856/http://www.hmml.org/centers/malta/history/history.html#Muslims |date=10 August 2013 }}</ref>\n*556 Completion of Justinian the Great's fortification of '''[[Saint Catherine's Monastery]]'''; a chapel and anchorites had already been there at least since the 4th century when [[Egeria (pilgrim)|Egeria]] visited in c. 385.<ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p.112.</ref> death of [[Cyriacus the Anchorite]].<ref>''[http://days.pravoslavie.ru/en/Days/20130929.htm September 29/October 12].'' Orthodox Calendar (PRAVOSLAVIE.RU).</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/saints/lives/2013/09/29/102813-venerable-cyriacus-the-hermit-of-palestine Venerable Cyriacus the Hermit of Palestine].'' OCA - Lives of the Saints.</ref><ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/759/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f4d\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u1f78\u03c2 \u1f41 \u1f08\u03bd\u03b1\u03c7\u03c9\u03c1\u03b7\u03c4\u1f74\u03c2].'' 29 \u03a3\u03b5\u03c0\u03c4\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref>\n*562 [[Isidorus of Miletus]] completes repair on dome of [[Hagia Sophia]], now higher by 20 feet than the [[Anthemius of Tralles|Anthemian]] original; re-[[Consecrations in Eastern Christianity#Consecration of a church|consecration]] of Hagia Sophia in Constantinople by [[Patriarch Eutychius of Constantinople|Patriarch Eutychius]] ([[December 23 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)|23 December]]).<ref>Great Synaxaristes: {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/1516/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u039c\u03bd\u03ae\u03bc\u03b7 \u1f18\u03b3\u03ba\u03b1\u03b9\u03bd\u03af\u03c9\u03bd \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u1f09\u03b3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03a3\u03bf\u03c6\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 (562 \u03bc.\u03a7.)].'' 23 \u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref>\n*565-566 Completion of the mosaic of the [[Transfiguration of Jesus|Transfiguration]] in [[apse]] of the Church of the Mother of God on Mt. Sinai.<ref name=\"TSAI114\"/>\n*565-78 The '''[[Cherubikon|Cherubic Hymn]]''' was added to the [[Divine Liturgy]] by Emperor [[Justin II]].\n*566 Bp. [[Longinus (missionary)|Longinus]] sent from Constantinople to Nubia as missionary.<ref name=TSAI114>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p.113.</ref>\n*568 '''[[Exarchate of Ravenna]]''' established, to 752, a Greek imperial outpost and place of contact with the [[Latin West]].<ref name=TSAI114/>\n*575 The ''Chronographia (\u03a7\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03af\u03b1)'' of [[John Malalas]] in 18 books, chronicles the years from creation to 563 AD.<ref>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p.114.</ref>\n*576 Dual hierarchy henceforth in Alexandria, [[Greek Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Chalcedonian (Greek)]] and [[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Monophysite (Coptic)]].\n*577 Patr. [[John Scholasticus|John III Scholasticus]] is responsible for the first collection of Canon Law, the [[Nomocanon]], of the [[Orthodox Church]].\n*580 Serious invasion of [[South Slavs#Interaction with the Balkan population|Slavs migrating into the Balkans and Greece]]; last recorded persecution of pagans in [[Byzantine Empire]].\n*582 Persecution of [[Monophysitism|Monophysites]] renewed under emperor [[Maurice (emperor)|Maurice]].\n\n\n*586 St. [[Saint Demetrius of Thessaloniki|Demetrios of Thessaloniki]] saves Thessaloniki from Avar-Slav siege.{{#tag:ref|[[Thessaloniki|Thessalonica]], the most important city in the Balkans except for the imperial capital, [[Constantinople]], was besieged by the Avars and their Slavic auxiliaries for seven days, as described in the ''[[Miracles of Saint Demetrius]]'', a collection of miracles attributed to the city's patron saint in two books, one written c. 610 and the other around 680.<ref>{{in lang|el}} Aikaterini Christophilopoulou. (2006). \"\u0392\u03c5\u03b6\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae \u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1. \u03a3\u03c7\u03b5\u03b4\u03af\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b5\u03c0\u03bf\u03c7\u03ae \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03ad\u03bb\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03c4' \u03bc\u03ad\u03c7\u03c1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c3\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0398' \u03b1\u03b9\u03ce\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2\". In: '''\u0392\u03c5\u03b6\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae \u0391\u03c5\u03c4\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1, \u039d\u03b5\u03ce\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2, \u03a4\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u0393'.''' Athens: Herodotos, 2006. pp.9\u201368. {{ISBN|9608256550}} (pp. 15,22).</ref><ref>{{in lang|de}} Walter Pohl. (1988). ''Die Awaren. Ein Steppenvolk in Mitteleuropa 567\u2013822 n. Chr..'' Munich: Verlag C.H. Beck, 1988. pp.101\u2013107. {{ISBN|3406333303}}</ref>\n:\"Like [[Sophronius of Jerusalem|Sophronius]] and other writers from this period, John (''Archbishop John of Thessaloniki, who composed his collection of Miracula in the 7th century'') underscored the effectiveness of the [[Intercession of saints|saint's intercession]] by demonstrating the primacy of [[Saint Demetrius of Thessaloniki|Demetrius]]' prayers over the activities of the angels. When, for example, during the Avar-Slav siege of September 586, the city was about to fall, John related that a high-ranking civilian dreamt that he saw two angels dressed as imperial guardsmen enter Demetrius' shrine and demand that he quit the city because God had ordered Thessalonica's destruction. But the saint resisted, telling the angels that the city's fate would be his: either God would relent when he heard the Saint's prayers, or he would 'perish' with the city. Shortly thereafter the city was saved and the efficacy of Demetrius' intercessions manifested. Indeed, the man who had the dream was certain that it was Demetrius who had saved the city because the figure he saw in the vision matched exactly 'the form in which he is represented in his ancient images'.\"<ref>Matthew Dal Santo. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=3p0YY3qnW6YC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false Debating the Saints' Cults in the Age of Gregory the Great].'' Oxford Studies in Byzantium. Oxford University Press, 2012. p.184. {{ISBN|9780199646791}}</ref>|group=note}}\n\n*c. 590 [[Parthenon]] in Athens converted into a Christian church dedicated to Agia Sophia.{{#tag:ref|\"Some modern writers maintain that the Parthenon was converted into a Christian sanctuary during the reign of [[Justinian I|Justinian]] (527\u201365)...But there is no evidence to support this in the ancient sources. The existing evidence suggests that the Parthenon was converted into a Christian basilica in the last decade of the sixth century.\"<ref>John Freely. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=QME9WXUnookC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false Strolling Through Athens: Fourteen Unforgettable Walks through Europe's Oldest City].'' 2nd Ed. Tauris Parke Paperbacks, 2004. p.69.</ref>|group=note}}\n*594 '''[[Evagrius Scholasticus]]''' writes ''Ecclesiastical History'', covering the years 431 to 594 AD.<ref>Glenn F. Chesnut. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Zoz6yRN44nMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false The First Christian Histories: Eusebius, Socrates, Sozomen, Theodoret, and Evagrius].'' 2nd Ed. Volume 46 of Th\u00e9ologie historique. Mercer University Press, 1986. p.216. {{ISBN|9780865541641}}</ref>\n*602 Final series of wars between Byzantine Empire and Sassanid Empire.\n*610 '''[[Heraclius]] changes official language of the Empire from Latin to [[Medieval Greek|Greek]]''', already the ''lingua franca'' of the vast majority of the population.\n*c. 611 [[Andreas of Caesarea]], Bp. of [[Kayseri|Caesarea]] in Cappadocia, writes the first Greek [[Church Fathers|Patristic commentary]] on the [[Book of Revelation]].<ref>Eugenia Scarvelis Constantinou. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=mM7aUdl9WB4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false Guiding to a Blessed End: Andrew of Caesarea and His Apocalypse Commentary in the Ancient Church].'' The Catholic University of America Press, 2013. 350 pp. {{ISBN|9780813221144}}</ref><ref>Eugenia Scarvelis Constantinou. ''[http://archimede.bibl.ulaval.ca/archimede/fichiers/25095/25095.pdf Andrew of Caesarea and the Apocalypse in the Ancient Church of the East].'' PhD thesis. Quebec: Universit\u00e9 Laval, 2008. 1026 pp. (.pdf)</ref>\n[[File:Vlahernskaya.jpg|thumb|left|160px|The Holy Virgin '''[[Blachernitissa]]''', divine protectress of the Byzantine Empire (''7th century'').]]\n*612 [[Holy Sponge]] and [[Holy Lance]] brought to Constantinople from Palestine.\n*617 Persian Army conquers Chalcedon after a long siege.\n*620 Slavs attack Thessaloniki.\n*626 '''[[Akathist|Akathist Hymn]] (''Chairetismoi'') to the [[Theotokos|Virgin Mary]]''' written, after Constantinople liberated from a [[Siege of Constantinople (626)|siege of 80,000 Avars, Slavs and the Persian fleet]].<ref>[[John Julius Norwich]]. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=FkUmAQAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y A Short History of Byzantium].'' New York, New York: Alfred A. Knoff, 1997. p. 92. {{ISBN|0-679-45088-2}}.</ref><ref name=\"\u0391\u03ba\u03ac\u03b8\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2-\u038e\u03bc\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2\">{{in lang|el}} ''[http://www.saint.gr/189/saint.aspx \u0391\u03ba\u03ac\u03b8\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u038e\u03bc\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2].'' \u039f\u03c1\u03b8\u03cc\u03b4\u03bf\u03be\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03b1\u03be\u03b1\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2. 19 April 2013. \u2013 (\u0395\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 16 \u03b7\u03bc\u03ad\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd \u03c4\u03bf \u0386\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf \u03a0\u03ac\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1).</ref>{{#tag:ref|According to various scholars, the Hymn is the product of other sieges of Constantinople that took place on later dates: at 860 by the Russians, 820 by the Slovaks, or at 671 and 717\u2013718 by the Moslems. Still others relate it to the \"[[Nika riots|Revolt of Nicas]]\" in 539. Most scholars, however, place the Hymn on the victory of August 626 against the Persians. And since Patriarch [[Sergius I of Constantinople|Sergios]]\u2019 name is closely associated with it, many researchers believe that he was the author of the Hymn.<ref>Emmy P. Karavellas. ''[http://www.orthodoxresearchinstitute.org/articles/liturgics/karavellas_akathist_hymn.htm THE AKATHIST HYMN].'' Orthodox Research Institute (Word Magazine, October 1975, pp. 12\u201313.). Retrieved: 17 May 2013.</ref> The Akathist Hymn (which in its present form was added to by many Ecclesiastical Hymnographers), existed for the most part even before it was formally accepted by the Church in 626 AD.|group=note}}\n*627 Emperor [[Heraclius]] decisively defeats Sassanid Persians at [[Battle of Nineveh (627)|Battle of Nineveh]], recovering [[True Cross]] and breaking power of the Sassanid dynasty.<ref>[[Walter Kaegi|Kaegi, Walter Emil]]. ''Heraclius: Emperor of Byzantium.'' Cambridge University Press, 2003. p. 168. {{ISBN|978-0-521-81459-1}}.</ref><ref>[[John Julius Norwich]]. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=ElLZK1EOjHsC&pg=PA92&redir_esc=y A Short History of Byzantium].'' Vintage Books, 1997. p. 94. {{ISBN|9780679772699}}</ref><ref>Charles Oman. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=N6A-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA212&redir_esc=y Europe, 476\u2013918].'' Periods of European history. Period I. Macmillan, 1893. p. 212.</ref>\n*630 '''Second [[Elevation of the Holy Cross]]''', on 21 March 630 AD,<ref>Baynes, Norman H (1912). ''\"The Restoration of the Cross at Jerusalem\".'' '''The English Historical Review''' 27 (106): 287\u2013299. p. 288. {{ISSN|0013-8266}}.</ref><ref>[[Walter Kaegi|Kaegi, Walter Emil]]. ''Heraclius: Emperor of Byzantium.'' Cambridge University Press, 2003. p. 206. {{ISBN|0-521-81459-6}}.</ref> when Emperor Heraclius entered Jerusalem amidst great rejoicing, and together with Patriarch Zacharios (609\u2013633), transferred the [[True Cross|Cross of Christ]] with great solemnity into the [[Church of the Holy Sepulchre|temple of the Resurrection]]; it is the only time a Byzantine emperor sets foot in the [[Holy Land]].\n*632 Christian influences on Islamic practice include [[Christian headcovering|veiling of women]], [[Hospitality ethics#Classical World|hospitality]] for monastic travellers, [[Prostrations#Christianity|prostrations]], facing east for prayer, fixed hours for daily office of prayer, [[Ablution in Christianity|ritual ablutions]] before worship.<ref name=TSAI-125>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p. 125.</ref>\n*633 Death of Patr. [[Modestus of Jerusalem]], who had restored many buildings after the [[Siege of Jerusalem (614)|Persian sack of 614]],<ref>[[Frederick Cornwallis Conybeare|F.C. Conybeare]]. ''[http://www.tertullian.org/fathers/antiochus_strategos_capture.htm Antiochus Strategos: The Capture of Jerusalem by the Persians in 614 AD].'' '''English Historical Review''' 25 (1910) pp. 502\u2013517.</ref> including the [[Church of the Holy Sepulchre#Rotunda and Aedicule|Rotunda of the Anastasis]].<ref name=TSAI-125/><ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/1483/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u039c\u03bf\u03b4\u03b5\u03c3\u03c4\u1f78\u03c2 \u1f08\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03b5\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f39\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03bf\u03bb\u03cd\u03bc\u03c9\u03bd].'' 18 \u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=103579 St Modestus the Archbishop of Jerusalem].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref>\n*634 Emperor Heraclius issues edict ordering all Jews to be baptized; many Jews flee to protection of Persians or Muslim Arabs.<ref name=TSAI-126>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. pp. 126\u2013127.</ref>\n*639 Death of Patr. '''[[Sophronius of Jerusalem|Sophronius I of Jerusalem]]''', whose poetry and prayers become part of the [[Divine Liturgy|Liturgy]], including the [[Troparion|Troparia]] of the [[Royal Hours]] chanted on [[Good Friday|Great Friday]] and the [[eve]]s of the [[Nativity of Jesus|Nativity]] and [[Epiphany (holiday)|Theophany]], and the main prayer of [[Great Blessing of Water]] on Theophany.<ref name=TSAI-126/>\n*641 St. [[Saint Christopher of Trebizond|Christopher of Trebizond]] heads the [[S\u00fcmela Monastery|Monastery of Panagia Soumela]].(641\u2013668).<ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=108982 St Christopher of Gazara].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref><ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/411/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u039f\u1f31 \u1f4d\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03b9 \u0392\u03b1\u03c1\u03bd\u03ac\u03b2\u03b1\u03c2, \u03a3\u03c9\u03c6\u03c1\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03a7\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03cc\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2].'' 18 \u0391\u03c5\u03b3\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref>\n*646 Alexandria recaptured by Muslim Arabs after a [[Byzantine-Arab Wars#Conquest of Egypt and Cyrenaica|Byzantine attempt to retake Egypt fails]], ending nearly ten centuries of [[Greco-Roman world|Greco-Roman]] civilization in Egypt;<ref>Alfred J. Butler. ''[https://archive.org/details/cu31924028717324 The Arab Conquest of Egypt and the last Thirty Years of the Roman Dominion].'' Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1902. pp.489\u2013491.</ref> the [[Monophysitism|monophysite]] Coptic patriarch [[Pope Benjamin I of Alexandria|Benjamin I]] and his followers willingly accept Arab rule, preferring it to the Byzantines;<ref name=TSAI-128>Dr. Kathryn Tsai. ''A Timeline of Eastern Church History.'' Divine Ascent Press, Point Reyes Station, CA, 2004. p. 128.</ref> [[Maximus the Confessor]] takes lead in opposing [[Monothelitism]].<ref name=TSAI-128/>\n*648 Pope [[Pope Theodore I|Theodore I of Rome]] excommunicates patriarch [[Patriarch Paul II of Constantinople|Paul II of Constantinople]].\n*649 Arabs invade and conquer Cyprus; the [[Lateran Council of 649]] in Rome definitively condemned [[Monothelitism]], being attended by 105 bishops, of which all but one were from the western portion of the Byzantine Empire.<ref name=ECONOMOU113>Ekonomou, Andrew J. ''Byzantine Rome and the Greek Popes: Eastern influences on Rome and the papacy from Gregory the Great to Zacharias, A.D. 590-752.'' Lexington Books, 2007. p. 113.</ref>{{#tag:ref|One-fourth of the bishops were (as indicated by their names) likely of Eastern ethnicity or origin and thus probably Greek-speaking.<ref name=ECONOMOU113/><ref>White, Lynn, Jr.. ''\"The Byzantinization of Sicily.\"'' '''The American Historical Review'''. Vol. 42, No. 1 (Oct. 1936). p.9.</ref>|group=note}}\n[[File:Byzantiumby650AD.svg|right|thumb|220px|Byzantine Empire by 650; by this year it lost all of its southern provinces except the Exarchate of Carthage.]]\n\n*c. 650 Sicily was flooded with an influx of Greek-speaking refugees from the East, both lay and clerical, from Syria and Egypt, due to a series of convulsions including the [[Sasanian conquest of Jerusalem|Persian invasion of 614]], the [[Muslim conquest of the Levant]] (634-638), and Emperor [[Heraclius]]' persecution of any who spoke out against [[Monothelitism]].<ref name=SICILY7-11>White, Lynn, Jr.. ''\"The Byzantinization of Sicily.\"'' '''The American Historical Review.''' Vol. 42, No. 1 (Oct., 1936). pp. 7-11.</ref>{{#tag:ref|\"From 614 onward the Levant suffered a series of fearful convulsions any one of which would have forced thousands of refugees across the sea. The first disaster was the Persian invasion under [[Khosrow II|Khusrau II]]... ...the migration to the Occident in the seventh century seems to have included almost no Coptic or Syriac speaking refugees; '''it was a purely Hellenic movement'''... ...Mohammedan histories show that a large proportion of the Greeks left the conquered regions, but it is difficult to distinguish the refugees in the Occident who retreated before the '''armies of Islam''', from those who had previously sought safety from '''the Persians''', and the '''persecution of Heraclius'''.\"<ref name=\"SICILY7-11\"/>|group=note}}\n*650 The Patriarchate of Constantinople counted 32 metropoles, or capitals of ecclesiastical provinces, 1 autocephalous metropolis, 34 autocephalous archbishoprics, and 352 bishoprics\u2013a grand total of 419 dioceses.<ref name=\"Vailh\u00e9\">Vailh\u00e9, Sim\u00e9on. ''\"[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/06752a.htm Greek Church].\"'' '''The Catholic Encyclopedia'''. Vol. 6. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1909. Retrieved: 15 May 2013.</ref>\n*654 Invasion of Rhodes by Arabs.\n*662 [[Parthenon]] in Athens rededicated in honour of the [[Theotokos|Mother of God]] as \"Panagia Atheniotissa\" (Panagia of Athens), becoming the fourth most important pilgrimage site in the Eastern Roman Empire after Constantinople, Ephesus and Thessalonica;<ref name=Kaldelis>Anthony Kaldellis Associate Professor (Department of Greek and Latin, The Ohio State University), [http://www.lsa.umich.edu/UMICH/modgreek/Home/_TOPNAV_WTGC/Lectures%20at%20U-M/ParthenonKaldellis.pdf ''A Heretical (Orthodox) History of the Parthenon''], p.3 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090824170528/http://www.lsa.umich.edu/UMICH/modgreek/Home/_TOPNAV_WTGC/Lectures%20at%20U-M/ParthenonKaldellis.pdf |date=24 August 2009 }}</ref> death of [[Maximus the Confessor]].\n*663-668 [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]] became the imperial seat of Emperor [[Constans II]], and passed to the [[Byzantine Rite|Greek Rite]] becoming the Metropolis of the whole Sicilian Orthodox Church.<ref>White, Lynn, Jr.. ''\"The Byzantinization of Sicily.\"'' '''The American Historical Review'''. Vol. 42, No. 1 (Oct. 1936). p.5.</ref>\n*669-78 '''[[Siege of Constantinople (674)|First Arab siege of Constantinople]]'''; at Battle of Syllaeum Arab fleet destroyed by Byzantines through use of [[Greek Fire]], ending immediate Arab threat to eastern Europe.\n*680\u2013681 '''[[Sixth Ecumenical Council]]''' held in Constantinople, condemning [[Monothelitism]] and affirming [[Christology]] of Maximus the Confessor, affirming that Christ has both a human will and a divine will; Patr. [[Sergius I of Constantinople|Sergius of Constantinople]] and Pope [[Pope Honorius I|Honorius of Rome]] are both explicitly [[anathema]]tized for their support of Monothelitism.\n[[File:1800 Wilkinson Map of the 4 Eastern Churches rectified.jpg|left|thumb|220px|Map of Justinian's [[Pentarchy (Christianity)|Pentarchy]], with almost all of modern Greece under Rome.]]\n\n*685 First monastics come to Mount Athos; emperor Justinian II is the first emperor to have the figure of the Lord [[Jesus Christ]] stamped on a [[Byzantine coinage|coin]].{{#tag:ref|The first [[Depiction of Jesus|portrait of Christ]] to appear on a coin may be on a [[Solidus (coin)|gold solidus]] of [[Marcian|Flavius Valerius Marcianus]], a senator who came to rule the Eastern Roman, or Byzantine, Empire from A.D. 450\u2013457. The coin appears to depict [[Christ]] bestowing a blessing on the [[Emperor of the East]] and his Empress, [[Aelia Pulcheria]]. But such [[Depiction of Jesus|images of Christ]] were far from popular until many years later.<ref>Edward Banning, (Special to The Globe and Mail). ''Byzantine Coins Led Way In Using Christ's Image.'' [[The Globe and Mail]]. Saturday 18 April 1987, Page C20.</ref>|group=note}}\n*688 Emperor [[Justinian II]] and Caliph [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|Abd al-Malik]] sign treaty neutralizing Cyprus.\n*692 The \"'''[[Pentarchy (Christianity)|Pentarchy]]'''\" form of government of universal Christendom by five patriarchal sees received formal ecclesiastical sanction at the '''[[Quinisext Council|Council in Trullo]]''', held in Constantinople, which ranked the five sees as ''Rome, Constantinople, Alexandria, Antioch'', and ''Jerusalem'';\n[[File:Byzantine-Arab naval struggle.png|right|thumb|220px|Byzantine-Arab naval struggles, c. AD 717\u20131025.]]\n\n*705 Long period of fighting begins between Trebizond in eastern Asia Minor and the Arabs.\n*706 Greek replaced by Arabic as administrative language in Egypt.<ref>[[Macquarie University]]: Faculty of Arts, Department of Ancient History. ''AHPG898 Coptic Dialects.'' Unit Guide Semester 1, 2012. p.15.</ref>\n*707 Byzantines lose Balearic Islands to Moors;\n*710 [[Pope Constantine]] makes last papal visit to Constantinople before 1967.\n*712 Death of '''[[Andrew of Crete]]''', [[bishop]], [[theologian]], [[homilist]], and [[hymnographer]].<ref>Great Synaxaristes {{in lang|el}}: ''[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/29/sxsaintinfo.aspx \u1f49 \u1f0d\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f08\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1\u03c2 \u1f41 \u1f39\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03bc\u03af\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2, \u1f08\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03b5\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03c1\u03ae\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2].'' 4 \u0399\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03af\u03bf\u03c5. \u039c\u0395\u0393\u0391\u03a3 \u03a3\u03a5\u039d\u0391\u039e\u0391\u03a1\u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u0397\u03a3.</ref><ref>''[http://oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=101894 St Andrew the Archbishop of Crete].'' OCA \u2013 Feasts and Saints.</ref>{{#tag:ref|A list of forty of his discourses, together with twenty-one edited sermons, is given in ''[[Patrologia Graeca]]'', XCVII, 801-1304.|group=note}}\n\n{{Timeline of Orthodoxy in Greece|state=expanded}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n*[[Early centers of Christianity]]\n*[[List of archbishops of Athens]]\n*[[Greek Orthodox Church]]\n*[[Orthodox Church organization]]\n'''History'''\n*[[History of the Orthodox Church]]\n*[[History of Eastern Christianity]]\n*[[History of the Eastern Orthodox Church under the Ottoman Empire]]\n*[[History of Eastern Orthodox Churches in the 20th century]]\n*[[Timeline of Eastern Orthodoxy in America]]\n'''Church Fathers'''\n*[[Apostolic Fathers]]\n*[[Church Fathers]]\n*''[[Ante-Nicene Fathers (book)]]''\n*[[Desert Fathers]]\n*''[[Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers]]''\n*[[List of Church Fathers]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{Dual |source=Orthodox Wiki |sourcepath=http://orthodoxwiki.org/index.php?title=Timeline+of+Orthodoxy+in+Greece&oldid=87849 |sourcearticle=Timeline of Orthodoxy in Greece |date=8 October 2009}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Rev. Dr. Veselin Kesich. ''[http://www.svspress.com/formation-and-struggles-part-1/?page_context=category&faceted_search=0 Formation and Struggles: The Birth of the Church AD 33-200]''. '''The Church in History Vol. I: Part I'''. Crestwood, N.Y. : St. Vladimirs Seminary Press, 2007. {{ISBN|9780881413199}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Meyendorff|first=John|author-link=John Meyendorff|year=1989|title=Imperial unity and Christian divisions: The Church 450-680 A.D.|series=The Churc